target: internal/ingest/orchestrator/compact_deletes.go
failure-mode: |
  The error check on the compaction-rewrite call site is inverted (== nil),
  so a failed segment.Rewrite is silently ignored and the pass records the
  un-rewritten segment as compacted — then advances the durable watermark
  past rows that were never physically removed. The exact segment-path
  sibling of m006 (merge cursor commit swallow): a swallowed persistence
  failure that turns fail-loud into silent non-compliance (deleted rows
  survive on disk permanently, and on ENOSPC the pass "succeeds" on a full
  disk). The inversion also errors on every CLEAN rewrite, so the healthy
  path breaks too.
expected-detection: |
  The segmentfault tier kills it at two layers in one `go test`:
    - oracle level: TestOracle_RestartSegmentFault_FailsLoudThenRecovers
      (rename-eio-compaction-rewrite arms IOOpRename ordinal 1 — only
      Patch/Rewrite rename, so the fault deterministically lands on the
      merge-tail compaction rewrite; under the mutant the error is swallowed,
      the lifecycle reaches the after-merge barrier, the observed-marker is
      never written, and the parent's require.FileExists fails).
    - orchestrator unit level: TestRunDeleteCompaction_ENOSPCRewriteReturnsFatalOperatorMessage
      requires the ENOSPC operator message out of runDeleteCompaction (the
      mutant returns success), and every healthy-path compaction test fails
      on the inverted clean-rewrite branch.
expected-tier: segmentfault
tiers: segmentfault

